iOS:

string interpolation: \()

vars/constants:
vars can change,  lets are constants and cannot change (compiler enforces immutability at compile time)

data types:
swift doesn't have primitive types but they provide primitive-like data types written in structs
string, int, double, bool
swift has two types (value and reference types). Value types are passed by value (copied) and Reference types are passed by reference and share single pointer

swift automatically infers the type from assigned value (type inference)
swift is a statically typed language (every value's type is known at compile time and mixing incompatible types requires explicit conversion, Swift never converts silently)

type annotation (explicitly stating the type)
let count: Int = 42

operators: functions with symbolic names 
arithmetic, comparison, logical

compound assignment
var score = 100
score += 10 // score = 110

control flow (execute based on decisions):
if / if else / ternary / switch / guard
let age = 20
let status = age >= 18 ? "Adult" : "Minor"

switch statements / or switch with ranges (must be exhaustive)

guard (exits early if condition isn't met)

loops (run code multiple times):
for i in 1..5 { }
do while (executes at least once as it checks conditions after first execution)

functions (first class citizens):
swift functions are first class citizens meaning that they can be stored in variables, passed as parameters, and returned from other functions). basically they are treated just like any other value
swift uses argument labels for clarity (can use _ to omit the label)
func greet(person name: String, from city: String) {
    print("Hello, \(name) from \(city)!")
}
greet(person: "Josh", from: "New York")

default parameter value
func greet(name: String = "World") {
    print("Hello, \(name)!")
}

Swift arrays use copy on write (assigning an array to a new variable shares storage until mutation)
Higher order functions (function that takes a closure as input) as opposed to for loop
.map (creates new object of returning type)
.compactMap (when you want to unwrap optionals and discard nil values)
.flatMap (flattens an object)
.filter (filters out based on condition)
.reduce (combine all elements by applying closure)


